<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="consistency-standards">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Apply Nielsen's Usability Heuristic #4 across five layers (internal, external, visual, functional, verbal) using a design system and consistency audits to eliminate cognitive load and user confusion.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>consistency</tag>
      <tag>design-system</tag>
      <tag>usability</tag>
      <tag>heuristics</tag>
      <tag>audit</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Consistency and Standards</title>

    <summary>Nielsen's Usability Heuristic #4: users should not have to wonder whether different words, situations, or actions mean the same thing. Apply in five layers — internal, external, visual, functional, and verbal — prioritizing industry conventions over product-specific ones. Enforce through a design system and regular consistency audits that count distinct variations of each UI element.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Inconsistency forces users to relearn the interface for each section, increasing cognitive load and error rates. When the same action behaves differently in different parts of the product, users lose confidence and slow down. A design system that governs components and terminology eliminates drift and makes consistency measurable (count variation instances, not subjective "feels consistent").</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When starting a design system from scratch — define the consistency hierarchy before building components.</item>
        <item>When auditing an existing product for usability issues — inconsistency is often the root cause of user confusion.</item>
        <item>When onboarding a new designer or developer — the design system is the reference.</item>
        <item>Before a brand refresh — audit all touchpoints against the new standards before shipping.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When intentional differentiation is the goal — e.g., a destructive action that must look visually distinct from standard actions. Purposeful inconsistency for contrast is valid.</item>
        <item>In early-stage exploration where standards have not been established — do not prematurely lock in patterns before validating with users.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="framework">
      <p>Consistency types, hierarchy, implementation patterns for visual/functional/verbal layers.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>A design system that governs components and terminology eliminates drift and makes consistency measurable through counting distinct variations of each UI element, not subjective assessment.</statement>
        <rationale>Measurable consistency prevents cognitive load by ensuring users learn once and apply that learning across the product. Measurable audits also detect drift early before it compounds across teams.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Defined consistency hierarchy">
        <description>A design system that specifies five layers of consistency: internal (within the product), external (against industry conventions), visual (colors, typography, spacing), functional (behavior patterns), and verbal (terminology, messaging). Each layer has explicit rules, and every component is checked against all five layers during design review.</description>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Undocumented consistency">
        <description>A product where designers agree "it feels consistent" but there is no documented spec. Different designers make different choices, and inconsistencies emerge across screens until a user complains.</description>
        <note>Without documentation, consistency becomes opinion and drifts under time pressure.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Prematurely locking in a consistency standard during early exploration before validating patterns with users.</description>
        <reason>Locking in too early means building the design system around an unvalidated pattern, which forces redesign or inconsistency when user research contradicts the pattern.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="audit-approach">
      <p>Regular consistency audits count distinct variations of each UI element and identify drift before it compounds. Audits surface stale component implementations, terminology conflicts, and visual deviations.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Consistency audits MUST count the number of distinct variations for each UI element type (buttons, modals, error messages, navigation items) and flag any variation not explicitly approved in the design system.</statement>
        <rationale>Counting forces visibility into drift. Subjective "looks consistent" assessments hide problems until they compound. Quantified audits also provide evidence for prioritizing standardization work.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Documented audit findings">
        <description>An audit discovers three distinct button styles in the codebase: button-primary, button-danger, and a custom styles.css version that does not match the design system. The audit report lists each variation, where it lives, and recommends consolidating to the design system components before the next release.</description>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Vague consistency review">
        <description>A designer reviews the product and says "it mostly looks consistent" but does not quantify variations or produce a report. Without evidence, cleanup work is hard to prioritize.</description>
        <note>Vague reviews do not drive action; quantified audits do.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Running consistency audits as a one-time big-bang exercise and expecting the result to hold without ongoing governance.</description>
        <reason>Inconsistency drifts immediately after the audit if there is no design system owner and no process to catch new violations. Ongoing audits (per component or feature) catch drift earlier and cost less to fix.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent can audit terminology consistency across a codebase or content set: given a list of strings (button labels, navigation items, error messages), the agent identifies duplicates with different wording, flags terminology not in the glossary, and recommends the canonical term. For visual consistency, agents work best when given structured design token output (JSON from Figma plugin or Style Dictionary) rather than screenshots — pixel-level comparison is not a reliable LLM task.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agents auditing terminology MUST work from a structured list of strings (extracted from code, Figma, or a content inventory) rather than screenshots. Agents auditing visual consistency MUST work from design token JSON (from Style Dictionary or Figma API) rather than asking the agent to visually compare pixels.</statement>
        <rationale>Structured input (strings, tokens, JSON) allows agents to compare systematically and produce reproducible results. Screenshots and pixel-level visual comparisons are unreliable LLM tasks and produce false positives.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Token-based consistency check">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[{
  "colors": {
    "primary": "#0066FF",
    "primary-dark": "#0052CC",
    "error": "#D32F2F",
    "error-dark": "#C62828"
  },
  "tokens_analysis": [
    {
      "issue_type": "naming_violation",
      "token_name": "primary-dark",
      "current_value": "#0052CC",
      "recommendation": "Rename to semantic token (e.g., primary-state-active) instead of value-based name"
    }
  ]
}]]></code>
        <note>Agent works with structured token data to flag naming violations and duplication.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Screenshot-based comparison">
        <description>Sending the agent two screenshots of buttons and asking it to compare visual consistency. Agent cannot reliably measure pixel dimensions, spacing, or font rendering differences.</description>
        <note>Pixel-level visual comparison should use automated tools (chromatic, visual regression testing) not LLM vision.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Do not ask an agent to both identify inconsistencies and generate the updated design system documentation in one call — scope creep degrades both outputs. Separate evaluation from generation.</statement>
        <rationale>Evaluation and generation are different cognitive tasks; combining them in one prompt produces shallow analysis. Better to audit first, then iterate on documentation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Terminology audit output will include false positives when the same word has legitimately different meanings in different contexts (e.g., "Archive" as action vs. "Archive" as section label). Always have a UX writer or product owner validate before enforcing.</statement>
        <rationale>Context-dependent terminology conflicts are common; the agent identifies candidates, humans validate.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>When auditing large codebases, provide the agent with an exclusion list or context about intentional variants (e.g., mobile vs. desktop button text). Without context, valid differences are flagged as inconsistencies.</statement>
        <rationale>The agent cannot distinguish intentional variation from drift; context prevents noise in the output.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>Tools for enforcing and auditing consistency.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Treat design tokens as the enforcement layer: if a value is not in the token file, it should not exist in production code. Make this a lint rule in your CI.</statement>
        <rationale>Lint rules catch token violations early and prevent accumulation of ad-hoc styling. Without linting, tokens become aspirational rather than enforced.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>CLI tools for consistency auditing and enforcement:</p>
      <list>
        <item><term name="style-dictionary">Build and lint design token files; validate naming. `npm i -g style-dictionary` / styledictionary.com</term></item>
        <item><term name="chromatic">Visual regression testing against Storybook baseline. `npm i -D chromatic` / chromatic.com</term></item>
        <item><term name="eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y">Lint JSX for accessibility convention violations. `npm i -D eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` / github.com/jsx-eslint/eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y</term></item>
        <item><term name="alex">Lint written content for inconsistent or insensitive language. `npm i -g alex` / alexjs.com</term></item>
        <item><term name="textlint">Enforce terminology rules in Markdown/HTML docs. `npm i -g textlint` / textlint.github.io</term></item>
      </list>

      <p>Services and platforms for consistency management:</p>
      <list>
        <item><term name="Figma">SaaS, REST API. Agent can pull all text nodes and component usages via API for consistency check.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Storybook">OSS. Run visual diffs via Chromatic; agents can generate story files for new components.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Zeroheight">SaaS. Design system documentation; no programmatic write API.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Supernova">SaaS, API. Design token sync from Figma to code; automation-friendly.</term></item>
        <item><term name="Style Dictionary">OSS. Token transformation pipeline; fully scriptable.</term></item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Establish a single source of truth for the approved glossary before auditing — without it, "canonical" choices become opinion battles.</item>
        <item>Assign a design system owner to triage new inconsistency reports; without an owner, findings accumulate without resolution.</item>
        <item>Run consistency audits incrementally (per component or feature) rather than as a one-time big-bang exercise; ongoing audits catch drift earlier.</item>
        <item>When resolving terminology conflicts, default to the platform convention (iOS HIG, Material Design, W3C) before internal preference.</item>
        <item>Document decisions with rationale: "we use 'Delete' not 'Remove' because…" — undocumented decisions get re-litigated.</item>
        <item>Agents cannot see rendered UI — they audit source code, token files, or exported strings; visual auditing still requires a human or a dedicated visual regression tool.</item>
        <item>Agents may suggest overly rigid canonical terms that reduce clarity — always have a UX writer or product owner validate the recommendation before enforcing.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/consistency-audit.md" purpose="Audit table: element, consistent Y/N, variations found, recommendation"/>
      <template path="templates/button-component.md" purpose="Design system component spec: variants, sizes, states, usage rules"/>
    </templates>

